,"1575":"1575","1539":"1539","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1549":"1549","Bristol, England, United Kingdom":"Bristol, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Downham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Downham, Cambridgeshire, England","Warmsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warmsworth, Yorkshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Wedmore, , Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England","England":"England","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, Frankrijk","England, United Kingdom":"Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1473–":"1473–Deceased","1470–1543":"1470–1543","1490–1588":"1490–1588","1505–1525":"1505–1525","1520–1579":"1520–1579","1524–1539":"1524–1539","1525–1575":"1525–1575","1527–Male":"1527–Deceased","1473–Female":"1473–Deceased","1473":"1473","1571":"1571","1470":"1470","1490":"1490","1525":"1525","1569":"1569","1558":"1558","1524":"1524","1579":"1579","1588":"1588","1543":"1543","1520":"1520","1575":"1575","1539":"1539","1505":"1505","1527":"1527","1549":"1549","Bristol, England, United Kingdom":"Bristol, England, United Kingdom","Downham, Cambridgeshire, England":"Downham, Cambridgeshire, England","Warmsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Warmsworth, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","Wedmore, , Somerset, England":"Wedmore, Somerset, England","England":"England","Metz, Moselle, Lorraine, France":"Metz, Moselle, France","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boso","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Italian: from the medieval personal name <i>Boso</i>, from an ancient Germanic personal name based on the element <i>bōs</i> ‘bad, evil, wild, angry’."],"variants":[{"name":"Bosetti","meanings":["Italian: patronymic or plural form of a pet form of the personal name   Boso  ."]},{"name":"Bosso","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Massimo, Philomena.","Italian:","from <i>bosso</i> ‘box tree’, probably applied as a topographic name but possibly also as a metonymic occupational name for a wood carver or turner."]},{"name":"Bosio","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Tino, Aida, Alberto, Aldo, Caterina, Mario, Roberto.  Spanish Julio, Adelmo, Alicia, Carlos, Jose, Juan, Lilia.  French Eloi, Remy.","Italian: from a variant of the medieval personal name   Boso  , Latinized as <i>Bosius</i>. This surname is also found in southern France."]},{"name":"Bosi","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Benoit.  Italian Antonio, Luciano, Silvio, Ugo.","Italian: patronymic or plural form of   Boso  . This surname is also found in southern France."]},{"name":"Bussone","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gilda.","Italian: from <i>Boson</i>, a inflected form of the ancient Germanic personal name   Boso  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":76,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":85,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. 